properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant winter weather expected Friday afternoon and Friday night. Total Snowfall: 15 to 30 cm over inland and higher terrain sections from Norman Bay to Cartwright, as well as the interior from Eagle River to Labrador City. Total Rainfall: 30 to 40 mm along the coast from Norman bay to Lodge Bay. Strongest Wind Gusts: near 60 km/h. Timespan: Beginning Friday near noon and lasting until Saturday morning. Remarks: Snow is generally expected inland with a mixture of either rain or non-accumulating wet snow along the coast from Cartwright to Norman Bay. Areas from Goose Bay and eastward may also experience significant periods of ice pellets Friday afternoon and Friday night. In western Labrador, strong wind gusts and cold temperatures will likely cause reduced visibility in snow and blowing snow Friday afternoon and Friday evening. Due to variations in the track of this system, precipitation totals remain uncertain, especially those expected Friday night. Updated totals will be provided in subsequent forecasts. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Poor weather conditions may contribute to transportation delays. Winter storm watches are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: First accumulating snowfall of the season may herald the arrival of November. A low pressure system will approach Ontario from the southwest. This weather system will bring a significant rainfall with it tonight through Thursday with many areas receiving a total of 20 to 40 mm of rain by Thursday evening. As the low passes by Thursday night, rain may change over to snow before tapering off Friday. Snowfall amounts of 2 to 4 cm are possible, especially over higher ground inland from Georgian Bay. There is uncertainty in the track of the low, which will affect how quickly the rain will change over to snow and subsequent snowfall amounts. Snow covered grass is possible for the first time this season Friday morning. This event will continue to be monitored. Poor winter driving conditions are possible Thursday night. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: First significant snowfall of the season expected overnight into Friday. Rain is expected today. Additional rainfall amounts of 15 to 25 mm are expected today for total amounts of 20 to 40 mm by this evening. Rain is expected to change over to snow overnight and taper off Friday. Snowfall amounts of 5 to 10 cm are possible by later Friday morning, especially inland from the Great Lakes and over higher ground. There is uncertainty in the track of the low, which will affect how quickly the rain will change over to snow and subsequent snowfall amounts. This event will continue to be monitored. Consider postponing non-essential travel as poor winter driving conditions are expected. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
